#errorCatcher Echo
##
## archive.json.tmpl — flat JSON snapshot of current/today/trend observation
## data, converted from the real dvmCombinedData PHP module. This replaces
## that PHP file's job for the front-end: instead of the JS guessing units
## from charts.json's hourly series (which is how the wind-speed/gust bug
## happened — those fields come through in the report's configured display
## unit, not bare m/s, and the front-end was assuming m/s), every value
## here goes through WeeWX's own $obj.format(...)/$unit.label tags, so it's
## already correctly converted to the report's real unit system. No more
## guessing.
##
## Deliberate differences from the original PHP, flagged rather than done
## quietly:
##   1. Missing-data fields use the JSON literal `null` (None_string="null")
##      instead of the PHP version's "0" — "0" reads as a real zero
##      reading, which isn't true when a sensor has no data at all.
##   2. Every *_time / *_maxtime / *_mintime field is a raw unix_epoch_ms
##      integer, not a server-formatted string like PHP's date('H:i', ...).
##      The PHP baked one fixed format per field (some 'H:i', some
##      'D j M H:i', some 'j M Y H:i') — formatting that client-side from
##      a raw timestamp is more flexible and matches how charts.json
##      already works throughout the rest of this project.
##   3. Found and fixed a real bug in the original barometer trend
##      cascade: the negative-side checks were ordered <0, then <-1, then
##      <-2, then <-3 — since <0 catches every negative value first and
##      the chain stops on first match, "Falling", "Falling Quickly" and
##      "Falling Very Rapidly" could never actually be reached; everything
##      negative collapsed to "Falling Slowly". Reordered to check the
##      most extreme case first, mirroring how the positive side already
##      did it correctly.
##   4. Fixed a second real bug, in the rain block: the "event" field's
##      $current.eventRain.format(...) call sat OUTSIDE the #try/#except
##      that was meant to guard storm_start_val above it. When eventRain
##      threw (not a recognised obs type for this binding), #errorCatcher
##      Echo's own placeholder syntax — ?'eventRain'? — leaked straight
##      into the JSON output as a bare token, which isn't valid JSON and
##      broke parsing of the entire file for every consumer. The format()
##      call now lives inside the same #try, with a safe "0" default set
##      beforehand, exactly like storm_start_val's own fallback.
##
## Page-theme/almanac concerns from the original file (ephem sun/moon
## ecliptic calculations, daylight-length, day/night body theme) are left
## out on purpose — they're not observation data, and astronomical.json
## already covers that ground (see the project's continuity notes). The
## trailing PHP includes (dvmColorMap.php, dvmAlmanacData.php,
## dvmUnitConversions.php, the commented-out meteor showers include) are
## likewise out of scope for an observations feed.
##
